article.description: Moriah Jefferson UConn with 17 points and the top-ranked Huskies, playing without two-time national player of the year Breanna Stewart, routed LSU 86-40 on Monday night.

video.headline: Connecticut cruises without Stewart
video.caption: Breanna Stewart misses the game with a sprained ankle, but it's no problem for Connecticut as Moriah Jefferson scores 17 points in an 86-40 victory over LSU.

video.title: Connecticut cruises without Stewart

article.headline: Top-ranked UConn routs LSU 86-40 despite Stewart's absence

images.name: Connecticut cruises without Stewart
images.caption: Breanna Stewart misses the game with a sprained ankle, but it's no problem for Connecticut as Moriah Jefferson scores 17 points in an 86-40 victory over LSU.

article.linkText: Top-ranked UConn routs LSU 86-40 despite Stewart's absence
article.story:
HARTFORD, Conn. -- Two-time national player of the year Breanna Stewart didn't play for top-ranked UConn against LSU. The Huskies didn't need her.

Moriah Jefferson led five players in double figures with 17 points and UConn routed the Tigers 86-40 on Monday night.

Morgan Tuck and Katie Lou Samuelson each scored 14 points and Gabby Williams chipped in with 13 to help UConn (9-0) to its 46th straight win.

Jefferson said with Stewart out, it was all about looking for whoever is open.

"There was a lot of good ball movement," said Jefferson, who also had seven assists. "There were a lot of assists and a lot of guys knocking in shots once we got the ball moving around."

Rina Hill led LSU (6-6) with 10 points.

UConn outscored LSU 35-6 off turnovers, 42-12 in the paint and 24-2 on the fast break.

The Huskies put on a defensive clinic, holding the Tigers to just 16 baskets on 54 shots (29.6 percent) and forcing 28 turnovers.

Stewart sprained right her right ankle when she came down on a teammate's foot in practice last week and as a precaution did not dress for the game. She was wearing dress flats on the bench.

"We've got another week," UConn coach Geno Auriemma said. "So I would expect that she'll be back to normal."

The 6-foot-4 senior leads the Huskies in scoring (22.9 points), rebounding (8.1) and blocked shots (27) this season. She had scored more than 20 points in six of UConn's first eight games. Stewart, who missed three games as a freshman, had played 92 consecutive games since missing the first round of the 2013 NCAA Tournament with an ankle injury.

But the Huskies didn't need her in this one. They never trailed.

Kia Nurse scored nine of her 11 points in the first quarter and UConn led 18-6 after 10 minutes.

Hill scored the first basket of the second quarter, but UConn went on an 18-2 run.

A rebound and put-back by Williams gave the Huskies their first 20-point lead with just under 6 minutes left in the first half, and the Huskies led 39-14 at intermission.

A 3-pointer by Jefferson from the left elbow pushed the lead past 30 points just 3 minutes into the second half.

"Coach actually said before the game that he doesn't want us to go in and think that we need to do what she does," said Samuelson, who got the start in place of Stewart. "Everyone just needed to do a little bit extra and contribute as a group."

The Huskies will have a week off before facing No. 6 Maryland on Dec. 28. Stewart is expected to be available for that game.

The Huskies also played without center Natalie Butler and guard Saniya Chong. Butler, a Georgetown transfer, has yet to play for the Huskies after having surgery in November to repair torn ligaments in her left thumb. Chong missed her third straight game with an IT band in her right leg.

LSU has been short-handed much of the season. The Tigers were playing without preseason All-SEC pick Raigyne Moncrief, who was averaging better than 10 points and seven rebounds a game when she was lost for the season to injury after seven games.

Sophomore Jenna Deemer came in leading LSU in scoring at 11.5 points per game but was held to just two points by Jefferson, missing all six of her shots from the floor.

"I think that is where we got to be more creative and with play action, whether we are playing Deemer off ball screens, playing off of hand-offs," LSU coach Nikki Fargus said. "There are some good possessions that we can build off of. This is only going to help us prepare for SEC play."

There was one scary moment in the fourth quarter. LSU's Akilah Bethel grabbed Williams right leg and threw her to the ground as the Husky sophomore was trying for an offensive rebound. Williams was down for a while, before walking off the court. Bethel received a flagrant foul.

TIP-INS

LSU: The Tigers have only beaten UConn once in their eight meetings. That happened during the regional finals in 2007 in Fresno, California when Sylvia Fowles led the Tigers to a 73-50 upset win. A newspaper photo of Fowles blocking Tina Charles' shot hung in Charles locker for the rest of her college career to remind her of the defeat. Charles led UConn to consecutive national titles in 2009 and 2010.

UConn: The Huskies maintained their top ranking in the AP Poll on Monday and are now 351-15 when playing as the No. 1 ranked team in the nation. Their last loss came against Stanford on Nov. 17, 2014.

UP NEXT:

LSU: The Tigers return from their two-game Northeast trip to face Samford at home on Dec. 28.

UConn: The Huskies travel to New York City, where they will face No. 6 Maryland on Monday. It will be the Huskies fifth game this season against a ranked opponent.
